		{"id":"d38843843984ff9d","type":"link","url":"https://notkey.studio/en/tutorials/godot-low-res-pixel-perfect-rendering-and-smooth-camera/","x":-12429,"y":-17267,"width":1040,"height":1003},
		{
			"id":"6958ac932ecc7b5f",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Game Loop\n### Defending yourself\nWhen playing as Pip, you are near the bottom of the food chain; there are creatures that are much more powerful than the player and will hunt you if they are hungry!\n\nPip is unique in that he is near defenseless on his own, only having a weak swipe ability. However, Pip starts with the unique ability to **pick up and throw** lightweight creatures and objects, which allows Pip to use external resources to solve situations. Pip can pick up a creature and squeeze it (by pressing the **Action** key) to make it cast its signature ability. Use this technique to interact with the environment OR kill creatures to steal their ability shards for yourself!\n\n### Map\nThe map is generated using a combination of room generation and cavelike noisy generation. The caves should be small enough that gameplay feels cohesive and tense but not overwhelmingly tight to be cramped.\n\n### Terrain\nTerrain is procedurally generated to appear cavelike.\nTerrain is interactable and can be destroyed or created. Tiles have special properties.\n\nWall tiles:\n- hardness: a modifier which alters how much damage the tile takes per hit.\n- health: when this reaches zero, the wall is destroyed.\n- inventory: stores these items. if destroyed, the wall drops these items.\n- interacted: keeps track of what entity last interacted with the tile.\n\n> Walls can have treasure or special items in them.\n\n> If there are special zones or environments behind walls, there should be visual evidence of a hidden area.\n\n### Encountering prefabs\nPrefab structures can be found in levels. They contain special creatures, items, or interactable entities. Most of the time, these structures can only be found or reached by using a special ability or under certain criteria.\n\n### Vision\nThe player can only see tiles of the room they are currently in. All entities on invisible tiles are also invisible. There may be rooms beyond walls that are hidden and must be broken into to discover.\n\n### The Anthurium\nThree arbitrary phases will occur during a round!\n\n**Phase 1**\n- The Anthurium is slow and its *Esoterica* has not had much time to flourish, so mostly Flowerings occur.\n- The player is able to peacefully explore the starting dungeon layout and discover what creatures inhabit the map.\n\n**Phase 2**\n- Blooms start, changing the conditions and makeup of the game board.\n- The ecosystem has matured slightly and developed.\n\n**Phase 3**\n- The Anthurium has spread throughout the board and blooms are more potent.\n- The Final Bloom is imminent, so the player must prepare.\n\n\nThe Final Bloom will occur when the Anthurium's *Esoterica* magnitude reaches over a certain threshold (50? 100? threshold increases per round completed? TBD)\n\nBe careful! If the dungeon is damaged too much, there's a chance that there will be an **Ichor famine**. It's very hard to come back from this, and the Anthurium is likely to die, causing all the inhabitants of the dungeon to starve as a result.\n\n##### When a round ends, \n- the Anthurium's esoterica will be reset to 0 \n- the anthurium's esoterica will rise faster\n- the threshold for the anthurium's final bloom will be higher, so more intense/potent blooms are more likely to happen as the run continues and the player completes rounds.\n- the map will be regenerated from a different seed\n- the anthurium will be placed in a random location on the map\n- the anthurium's size will be reset down to its initial size\n- creature spawns will be reset and randomized\n- some rare creatures encountered in the last round are more likely to be encountered in following rounds\n\nTechnically, the game can go on infinitely if the player is skilled enough.\n\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-8260,
			"y":-5021,
			"width":940,
			"height":1640
		},
		{
			"id":"468eabc50645906e",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Anthurium\n\nPlay as Pip, a little animal with many tricks up his sleeve. Befriend, defeat, and interact with the many beasts found in Dreamland to survive. Survive as long as you can throughout Dreamland and discover the mystery of the Anthurium, a mysterious ancient reality-warping plant deity.\n\nAnthurium is a modern top-down survival and exploration arcade game with low fidelity graphics and a bizarre, familiar yet otherworldly aesthetic. Anthurium leans into emergent gameplay elements, where simple elements come together to make an experience much much greater than the sum of its parts.\n\nCurrently, the game is set on a board of 64x64 tiles and has no narrative story elements aside from environmental storytelling, but this can change as development continues throughout the years.\n\nPlayers are placed in an evolving sandbox where they are free to explore a variety of creatures and events (perhaps characters later on?).",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-8260,
			"y":-5601,
			"width":645,
			"height":520
		},
		{
			"id":"a6fb311fbf3e5b68",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Controls\n*Anthurium* is a game meant for controllers and does not make use of the mouse at all.\n\n| Name                 | Button   |\n| -------------------- | -------- |\n| Movement/Select      | LS/D-Pad |\n| Ability 1            | A        |\n| Ability 2            | B        |\n| Ability 3            | X        |\n| Ability 4            | Y        |\n| Modifier             | LT       |\n| Interact with nearby | RB       |\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-7575,
			"y":-5601,
			"width":600,
			"height":420
		},
		{
			"id":"8570bd6bf4c141a5",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Creatures\nEach creature is separated into categories which describe its basic behaviors and tendencies. More primitive creatures have a drive to live, survive, and reproduce. Other creatures have other goals that they pursue.\n\n| Behavior Class | Description                                                           |\n| -------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| PASSIVE        | Does not attack other creatures OR flees when nearby other creatures. |\n| REACTIVE       | Only retaliates if provoked.                                          |\n| PREDATORY      | Actively hunts other creatures to satiate itself.                     |\n| FERAL          | Violent towards other creatures.                                      |\n| ALOOF          | Does not care about other creatures.                                  |\n\n| Consumer Type | Description                                                 |\n| ------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- |\n| AMBIENT       | Ichor is replenished passively over time given a condition. |\n| PROXIMITY     | Ichor is replenished when nearby a specific entity.         |\n| CONSUMER      | Ichor is replenished by consuming entities                  |\n| ESOTERIC      | Ichor is replenished through unconventional means.          |\n| EXEMPT        | Does not have ichor.                                        |\nCreatures will have emergent relationships with each other through their needs and behaviors (without explicitly scripted events). Creature relationships are not hardcoded, instead creatures will react to others based on their actions and intent.\nCreatures can interact with, damage, heal, use abilities on, move with, and generally affect other entities, including the Anthurium.\n\nThe potential is endless for how creatures utilize their environment and what kind of behaviors they have.\n\n\n### Abilities\nEvery creature has four **Ability Slots**. The portable form of an ability is an **Ability Shard**. Technically, every creature can discard abilities. The player can discard an ability by pausing the game and accessing a menu where they manage their abilities. Creatures can discard their abilities and drop an Ability Shard on the floor, freeing up an Ability Slot. The player is allowed to rearrange their abilities into different slots if they wish. \n\nSome abilities can only be used a few times before the shard is destroyed.\n\nSome abilities have cooldowns or cast times.\n\nSome abilities cost Ichor to cast.\n\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-7235,
			"y":-4861,
			"width":740,
			"height":1020
		},
		{
			"id":"e8388fadd0e8a5ec",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Ichor\nIchor is the lifeblood of the dungeon and acts as the liquid energy that creatures use to stay alive and flourish.\n\nThe Anthurium is the dungeon's primary Ichor source. It slowly generates Ichor, which it uses to beat its heart and bloom. It produces fruit which have a high concentration of Ichor. A larger Anthurium network means more Ichor generated, meaning more Ichor flowing into the ecosystem.\n\nThe Anthurium can also be predatory and eat creatures or terrain when it's either low on Ichor or cannot produce enough on its own.\n\nIchor transfer happens through\n- creatures dying and dropping meat/food on the ground\n- predators eating prey directly\n- symbiotic creatures absorbing ichor directly from anthurium\n\nDiminishment:\n- passive time decay on every creature\n- ability usage\n- bloom events consuming ichor from the network to fire\n- ichor lost to entropy on creature death\n\nMultiplication:\n- closed predator/prey loops\n- high felicity accelerates root generation\n- creature reproduction introduces new ichor containers into the ecosystem\n- dense food sources act as injections\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-6925,
			"y":-5601,
			"width":860,
			"height":700
		},
		{
			"id":"9af20d522b29e1ec",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Anthurium\nSix emotional parameters (*Esoterica*) track the Anthurium's state.\nThey are:\n- *Felicity* (joyful contentment)\n- *Furor* (divine rage)\n- *Lacuna* (hollow emptiness)\n- *Tremendum* (awe-inspiring power)\n- *Acedia* (torpor and apathy)\n- *Anamnesis* (awakening and recalling)\n\nWhen it blooms, those six values form a vector that selects the nearest matching `BloomEvent` by cosine similarity. The vector's angle picks the event; its magnitude sets how intense it is.\n\nThere are two bloom tiers.\n- Bloom (significant dunegon-altering event)\n- Final Bloom (boss event, ends the round)\n\n### Heartbeat\nThe Anthurium pulses on a semi-regular interval, sending a small amount of bloom potential through its root network. Potential flows outward and accumulates at end nodes (the outermost roots). When an end node's accumulated potential crosses a threshold, it blooms.\n\nThis means:\n- a larger network = more end nodes = potential is spread thinner, blooms are slower per end node that exists! (the anthurium will need to create more hearts to beat stronger)\n- a severed or small network = potential concentrates = blooms fire faster and harder\n- the player can influence bloom timing by suppressing or letting the Anthurium grow\n##### Flowering\nThe Anthurium has a small chance to do one of these things every heartbeat.\n\n- Extends a root 2-3 tiles in a direction toward the nearest unclaimed space\n- Spawns a single passive creature near a root end\n- Releases an ichor mote that drifts toward the nearest hungry creature\n- Reinforces a wall tile near a root (raises hardness)\n\n### Bloom Events\nBloom events are unpredictable chaotic events that affect the dungeon in some aspect; changing the terrain, summoning entities, altering the state of the Anthurium itself, changing the rules of the game, etc. can all be Bloom Events. Here are some examples:\n\n##### Bloom Event Examples\n- the anthurium begins drawing ichor from nearby creatures\n- jumpy bug swarp with mother bug appearance, kill her to stop the swarm (when mother is killed, all bugs instantly die dropping nutritious meat)\n- a sinkhole opens up with a dragon worm inside\n- the plant goes into overdrive, spreading and eating all matter aggressively\n- interdimensional alien beings invade\n- nine wizards appear and start transforming the dungeon\n- the anthurium is split into multiple fragments spread out all across the board\n- everything lights on fire\n- everything turns into a swamp\n- the undead come back to life\n- the dungeon's zones are picked up and moved around\n- magic, colorful, unstable living crystals grow forth from the anthurium\n- summon a powerful creature\n\n\n### Esoterica\nThe Anthurium keeps track of six parameters as it lives on in the dungeon.\n\n| *Esoterica*                                       | Rises When...                                                                                                                                                                                                     | Falls when...                                             |\n| ------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------- |\n| *Felicity*<br>(Things are as they should be)      | - the Anthurium network spreads<br>- creatures are born from blooms<br>- ichor is plentiful in the dungeon                                                                                                        | - creatures are killed                                    |\n| *Furor*<br>(Divine anger triggered by violation)  | - Anthurium parts are damaged or destroyed<br>- when a creature born from the Anthurium is killed<br>- terrain near the Anthurium is destroyed                                                                    | - time elapses                                            |\n| *Lacuna*<br>(The ache of absence)                 | - rooms are empty of creatures<br>- the Anthurium's network has been severed or fragmented<br>- a long time has elapsed without a bloom<br>- items are used or consumed                                           | - entities are created/summoned<br>- terrain is changed   |\n| *Tremendum*<br>(Awe inspired by scale and power)  | - large amounts of damage occur in a short period<br>- when a powerful creature dies<br>- when the network reaches a new size threshold                                                                           | - time elapses                                            |\n| *Acedia*<br>(Hollow spiritual numbness/festering) | - the Anthurium hasn't interacted with or been interacted with a creature for some time<br>- it doesn't have enough room to grow<br>- the anthurium is starved and unable to beat its heart at full effectiveness | - the plant spreads<br>- entities interact with the plant |\n| *Anamnesis*<br>(A spiritual recalling to memory)  | - time elapses<br>- the Anthurium absorbs ichor over the run                                                                                                                                                      | - the plant's parts are destroyed                         |\n\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-6415,
			"y":-4861,
			"width":1400,
			"height":1760
		},
		{
			"id":"1a627c7142f7b7ff",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Aura\nAura is a reflection of the vitality of the arena and is the score-keeping metric for runs.\n\nAura rises when the ecosystem is thriving (creatures/anthurium alive, ichor plentiful, terrain intact).\nAura falls when things are dying or being destroyed recklessly.\nThe player can drain Aura for short-term gain (kill things for special items/shards) or cultivate it for a stronger result screen score and a harder but richer Final Bloom. Aura at the moment the Final Bloom fires becomes the run's score multiplier.\n\nAura rises when\n- Creatures are alive and active (multiplied by how many different creature species are active on the map)\n- The anthurium spreads\n- Terrain is intact\n- Ichor is abundant\n\nAura falls when\n- Creatures die\n- The anthurium is suppressed or killed back\n- Terrain is destroyed\n- Ichor goes scarce\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-6015,
			"y":-5621,
			"width":620,
			"height":600
		},
		{
			"id":"78feac18860f74a7",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Results screen\nWhen the player dies or completes a round, a results screen will prompt the player to either quit the run or continue.\n\nThe results screen tallies up the final score and shows various metrics and data which reflect what happened and what the player did during the round.\n\nScoring formula for round end:\n```\nFinal score\n =\t(Distinct creature species ever active x 200)\n +\t(Anamnesis at Final Bloom x 50)\n +\tif the player survives: (Aura at Final Bloom x 100)\n +\telse if the player dies: (Total Aura x 50)\n +\t(Boss completion bonus)\n -\t(Anthurium damage taken x 10)\n```\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-5315,
			"y":-5621,
			"width":500,
			"height":420
		},
		{
			"id":"799c243927e3c4da",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Run-to-run progression\n\nThe player unlocks more content based on\n- high scores\n- amount of runs played\n- unique quests completed?\n- achievements\n\nUnlockables include\n- Additional creature types that can appear in the dungeon\n- Additional bloom events\n- Additional terrain types (zones/biomes?)\n- Cosmetics for pip and other creatures\n- Bestiary pages\n- Additional fun modes\n- other things?",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-4915,
			"y":-4801,
			"width":520,
			"height":520
		},
		{
			"id":"0dc65f3f8cfbb09f",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# design 3\n\n| design 3                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          |\n| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| the player starts inside a room (a room in the level) which can be broken out of using the things present in the room                                                                                                                             |\n| the player must collect enough life points to open a door to advance to the next level                                                                                                                                                            |\n| the game's pacing relies on multiple factors<br>- how easy it is to kill creatures<br>- how creatures spawn<br>- how creatures group up together<br>- how the player navigates around the world<br>- how easy it is for the player to break tiles |\n| wall tiles have different properties: hardness, health, last_interacted, a stack inventory, etc                                                                                                                                                   |\n| the player does not have vision of the space outside a room                                                                                                                                                                                       |\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-13536,
			"y":-5754,
			"width":460,
			"height":440
		},
		{
			"id":"5cf9e89375eb8844",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# design 1\n| design 1                                                                                    |\n| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| creatures have innate hunger value which depletes over time                                 |\n| creatures have a list of priority sustenance methods                                        |\n| the anthurium is the only thing in the dungeon providing consumable nutrition to herbivores |\n| creatures will seek out their preferred food sources, as is their primary behavior          |\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-14027,
			"y":-5754,
			"width":460,
			"height":290
		},
		{
			"id":"b393480d8f70c009",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"The Anthurium is an ancient godlike plant entity who is trapped in dreamland. The Anthurium's goals are unknown to mortals.\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-11410,
			"y":-5781,
			"width":300,
			"height":120
		},
		{
			"id":"ccd7eb47c4405b0c",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"you are a capable small animal with many abilities and tricks up his sleeve. your goal is to go as far as you can through a dungeon and discover the mystery of the anthurium (a ravenous godlike plant entity which transmutes matter into more of itself). you are in the lower middle of the fantastical food chain of this place (dreamland) and must navigate through these environments while surviving and avoiding being killed.",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-13981,
			"y":-5981,
			"width":460,
			"height":200
		},
		{
			"id":"7c82bf55f17c5d32",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Aura\nAura has a floor that rises with *Anamnesis*. Early-run Aura can be zero, but late-run Aura has a minimum because the Anthurium's very presence creates vitality. This means a player can recover Aura but can't completely hollow out the ecosystem and expect to recover in the last few minutes.\n\nAura gates Final Bloom quality. When the Final Bloom triggers, the current Aura value is locked in as a modifier to the boss encounter.\n\n```\nHigh Aura: the boss event is at its full difficulty and capabilities; it's quite dangerous but much richer in its unlocks and has a bigger score multiplier.\n\nLow Aura: the boss event is more lame and weak. It's easier but there's less of a score multiplier.\n```\n\nAura spent = Aura borrowed. When the player kills for ability shards or resources, the Aura drops. But they can \"invest\" those resources back: a player who uses a shard to trigger a chain event that helps the ecosystem recover can boost Aura.\n\nScoring formula:\n```\nFinal score\n =\t(Aura at Final Bloom x 100)\n +\t(Anamnesis at Final Bloom x 50)\n +\t(Distinct creature species ever active x 200)\n +\t(Boss completion bonus)\n -\t(Anthurium damage taken x 10)\n```\n\nProgression unlocks via score tiers:\n- new creature types enter the spawn pool\n- new BloomEvents become available\n- new prefab structure types appear\n- cosmetics for pip\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-9880,
			"y":-5520,
			"width":460,
			"height":1120
		},
		{
			"id":"05fd29f2d987b371",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Events - Bloom\n\n*Verdant Surge*\nThe network extends rapidly across several tiles, spawning some passive creatures from new end nodes. Ichor nodes appear nearby. The dungeon should feel abundant.\nAt high potency, grow more roots and plants and spawn more creatures.\n\n*Umbrage*\nThe Anthurium spawns a creature that is specifically hostile nearby the creature that last damaged its network.\nAt high potency, spawn more and smarter creatures.\n\n*Hollow*\nA zone goes completely silent. All creatures within it flee or freeze. A unique creature appears with the need to find something.\n\n*Witness*\nThe Anthurium has witnessed something powerful die. A large, impressive root structure erupts near that location. A powerful predatory creature spawns from it.\nAt high potency, the creature is more powerful and larger.\n\n*Captor*\nThe Anthurium will block off entrances to zones with strong roots",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-9350,
			"y":-5430,
			"width":480,
			"height":940
		},
		{
			"id":"6ad35bda1ffdcdc6",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"With this solution, magnitude is no longer another dimension deciding what kind of event occurs. Instead, it acts as a `potency` value that modifies the `BloomEvent` itself.\n\nI'll have to get creative deciding how events scale with potency.\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-9900,
			"y":-5825,
			"width":400,
			"height":209
		},
		{
			"id":"2acc6c70ca9ca7f7",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Player dies",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-18190,
			"y":-6057,
			"width":190,
			"height":100
		},
		{
			"id":"a22f93445020bb22",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Results screen",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-18500,
			"y":-5816,
			"width":340,
			"height":190
		},
		{
			"id":"88910bde6a74f36a",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"\n\n\n| input movement                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      | input abilities                                                                                                                                                                       | behavior (AI)                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   |\n| ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| Interfaced with by using `InputComponent.move_input_direction`.<br>This variable is ONLY a direction and is normalized.<br>`InputComponent.move_input_direction` is equivalent to an analog stick on a controller; when it is 0, no movement is expected, when it is not equal to 0, it is expected that the creature will move using its special `movement_function()`, which transforms that direction into a method of movement. | Interfaced with by using `InputComponent.press_action()` and `InputComponent.release_action()`.<br>These functions are equivalent to pressing and releasing a button on a controller. | The `StateMachine` has a boolean variable `use_inputs` which defaults to `true`.<br>When `use_inputs` is false, no state will be able to modify any parameters from `InputComponent`.<br>This means that the player can technically control any creature by adding a `PlayerController` component to a creature, which gives the player an interface to directly control the creature's inputs, rather than the `StateMachine`. |\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-14147,
			"y":-4701,
			"width":1160,
			"height":340
		},
		{
			"id":"95e91f5667079eb3",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Bloom Events\nThe Anthurium has a heartbeat. Every few seconds, the Anthurium will pulse, carrying a small amount of *bloom potential*. When an end node accumulates enough potential, it blooms.\n\n**How does the Anthurium spread and grow?**\n\n### Esoterica\n`BloomEvent`s store these six esoterica as constants.\n\nWhen a bloom is triggered, the Anthurium will take its current esoterica values as a six-dimensional `bloom_vector` and will iterate through all `BloomEvent`s, finding the event that has the closest vector to the current values.\n\n**Should magnitude be considered as a factor for distance (should the function just consider the angle between vectors)? What if magnitude just affected how potent an event is? This means that every event would have a potency parameter that changes how the event behaves for different magnitudes.**\n\nThere are three types of Blooms:\n1. Flowering (small event that does not need notification or basic anthurium actions like spawning creatures or growing)\n2. Bloom\n3. Final Bloom (event that is required to beat the level)",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-11410,
			"y":-5620,
			"width":440,
			"height":820
		},
		{
			"id":"fc8626115d07b471",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# design 2\n| design 2                                                                                                                                        |\n| ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| creatures do not have hunger                                                                                                                    |\n| creatures simply wander around randomly or have other positional goals led by some other mechanism                                              |\n| player has a magic meter which is filled by killing creatures                                                                                   |\n| killing creatures is a way of propagating energy back into the environment<br>creatures disappear into items which can be consumed by creatures |\n| the player's magic meter can be used to channel a crystal to upgrade enemies around it                                                          |",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-14027,
			"y":-5444,
			"width":460,
			"height":350
		},
		{
			"id":"7ed4ff56a3c1999b",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"If i wanted to expand the game into zones like i originally wanted, i can split the game world into chunks. That way, i dont have to simulate every tile of the anthurium spreading, i can just store a percentage for each chunk. And when the chunk is loaded, i can generate anthurium tiles based on adjacent chunk percentages.",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-14147,
			"y":-5061,
			"width":300,
			"height":240,
			"color":"1"
		},
		{
			"id":"9127388e9142e797",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"\n```gdscript\nextends Resource\nclass_name BloomEvent\n\nvar archetype: Esoterica\nvar type: BloomType\nvar min_anamnesis: float\n\nfunc execute(potency: float) -> void:\n\tpass\n```\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-11270,
			"y":-4640,
			"width":320,
			"height":240
		},
		{
			"id":"67507ad359327fb9",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"```gdscript\nextends Variant\nclass_name Esoterica\n\nvar felicity: float\nvar furor: float\nvar lacuna: float\nvar tremendum: float\nvar acedia: float\nvar anamnesis: float\n\nfunc _init(fe: float = 0.0, fu: float = 0.0, la: float = 0.0, tr: float = 0.0, ac: float = 0.0, an: float = 0.0) -> void:\n\tfelicity = fe\n\tfuror = fu\n\tlacuna = la\n\ttremendum = tr\n\tacedia = ac\n\tanamnesis = an\n\nfunc to_array() -> Array[float]:\n\treturn [felicity, furor, lacuna, tremendum, acedia, anamnesis]\n\nfunc magnitude() -> float:\n\treturn sqrt(felicity**2 + furor**2 + lacuna**2 + tremendum**2 + acedia**2 + anamnesis**2)\n\nfunc normalized() -> Esoterica:\n\tvar m: float = magnitude()\n\tif m == 0.0: return Esoterica.new()\n\treturn Esoterica.new(felicity/m, furor/m, lacuna/m, tremendum/m, acedia/m, anamnesis/m)\n\nfunc dot(other: Esoterica) -> float:\n\treturn felicity*other.felicity + furor*other.furor + lacuna*other.lacuna + tremendum*other.tremendum + acedia*other.apophenia + anamnesis*other.anamnesis\n\nfunc cosine_similarity(other: Esoterica) -> float:\n\tvar denom: float = magnitude() * other.magnitude\n\tif denom == 0.0: return 0.0\n\treturn dot(other) / denom\n\n```\n\n\n\n```gdscript\nfunc select_bloom_event(current: Esoterica) -> BloomEvent:\n\tvar best_event: BloomEvent\n\tvar best_score: float = -INF\n\tfor event in bloom_events:\n\t\tvar similarity: float = current.cosine_similarity(event.archetype)\n\t\tif similarity > best_score:\n\t\t\tbest_score = similarity\n\t\t\tbest_event = event\n\treturn best_event\n\t\nfunc trigger_bloom() -> void:\n\tvar state: Esoterica = get_current_esoterica()\n\tvar event: BloomEvent = select_bloom_event(state)\n\tvar potency: float = state.magnitude()\n\tevent.execute(potency)\n```\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-10860,
			"y":-5870,
			"width":840,
			"height":1180
		},
		{
			"id":"22eb53a37b5f06e2",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Events - Flowering\n- Extends a root 2-3 tiles in a direction toward the nearest unclaimed space\n- Spawns a single passive creature near a root end\n- Releases an ichor mote that drifts toward the nearest hungry creature\n- Reinforces a wall tile near a root (raises hardness)",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-9350,
			"y":-5825,
			"width":480,
			"height":360
		},
		{
			"id":"bd86ed7ae5f07b9b",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# final design of game loop\n\nPlay as Pip, a little animal with many tricks up his sleeve. Befriend, defeat, and interact with the many beasts found in Dreamland to survive. Traverse as far as you can throughout Dreamland and discover the mystery of the dangerous Anthurium, a ravenous, godlike plant entity which transmutes matter into more of itself.\n\n---\n\n# Start\n### Tutorial\n\nThe game should not need instructions to play; the controls should be intuitive and there should be visual effects that lead the player in the correct direction for progression.\n\nAt the beginning of the game, the player is locked in a small room with an Anthurium Flower, the **Pick Up / Drop** Ability Shard and a digger creature.\nThe player must activate the shard, then pick up the digger creature and use its ability to escape the room.\n\n## Dynamic Elements\nFrom run to run, these things change:\n- Map layout\n- Prefab structures\n- Creatures inhabiting the map\n- Resources on the map\n- Nutrition sources\n- Starting position of the Anthurium\n\n\n---\n\n# Game Mechanics\n\n### Controls\n*Anthurium* is a game meant for controllers and does not make use of the mouse at all.\n\n| Name            | Keybind     | Button   |\n| --------------- | ----------- | -------- |\n| Movement/Select | WASD        | LS/D-Pad |\n| Ability 1       | SPACE       | RT       |\n| Ability 2       | P           | B        |\n| Ability 3       | O           | X        |\n| Ability 4       | I           | Y        |\n| Action/Interact | ENTER       | A        |\n| Back            | BACKSPACE   | B        |\n| Accept          | ENTER/SPACE | A/RT     |\n\n### Abilities\nEvery creature has four **Ability Slots**. The portable form of an ability is an **Ability Shard**. Technically, every creature can discard abilities. The player can discard an ability by pausing the game and accessing the menu. Pressing a button on an ability will discard it and drop that Ability Shard on the floor, freeing up an Ability Slot. The player is allowed to rearrange their abilities into different slots if they wish. Some abilities can only be used a few times before the shard is destroyed.\n\n### Ichor\n> might rename this?\n> (ichor dew aether flow shimmer syrup mana mercury argent aura mote vitae)\n\nEvery creature has a value which acts as a hunger, energy, and mana resource. The resource is called **Ichor**. Ichor drains over time but can be replenished by consuming food or other special items. It is drained by using special abilities. When Ichor is drained completely, the creature will take damage over time.\n> Ichor acts as a drive for creatures to seek food and replenish themselves, making creature behavior more interesting and complex\n> Ichor also acts as motivation for the player to not only survive, but also to strategically use abilities only when necessary\n\n### Terrain\nTerrain is procedurally generated to appear cavelike.\nTerrain is interactable and can be destroyed or created. Tiles have special properties.\n\nWall tiles:\n- hardness: a modifier which alters how much damage the tile takes per hit.\n- health: when this reaches zero, the wall is destroyed.\n- inventory: stores these items. if destroyed, the wall drops these items.\n- interacted: keeps track of what entity last interacted with the tile.\n\n> Walls can have treasure or special items in them.\n\n### Map\nThe map is procedurally generated using a combination of room generation and cavelike noisy generation. The caves should be small enough that gameplay feels cohesive and tense but not overwhelmingly tight to be cramped.\n\n### Vision\nThe player can only see tiles of the room they are currently in. All entities on invisible tiles are also invisible. There may be rooms beyond walls that are hidden and must be broken into to discover.\n\n### The Anthurium\nThe Anthurium acts as a natural and dynamic time limit that the player has to work around.\nThe Anthurium has multiple parts that function differently.\n\n| PART   | DESCRIPTION                                                                                                                                       |\n| ------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| Core   | Acts as the brain of the Anthurium. If all the cores are killed, the plant dies.                                                                  |\n| Shield | Protects nearby parts.                                                                                                                            |\n| Spine  | Actively tries to stab creatures with its poisonous needles. If a creature is sufficiently poisoned, it passes out.                               |\n| Flower | Produces fruit. Fruit carry seeds which produce a new core if left alone. There are a vast number of fruits; a random one is produced every time. |\n| Leaf   | Produces extra amounts of nutrition for the Anthurium.                                                                                            |\n| Root   | Traps incapacitated creatures and slowly kills them and eats them.                                                                                |\nThe Anthurium has a property *aggression* which determines what kind of parts the plant grows. The more aggression the plant has, the more likely it produces spines and roots. The less aggression the plant has, the more likely it will produce leaves and shields. Aggression is increased when creatures are nearby a plant part, and is increased even more strongly if a part is attacked. Aggression is also inversely proportional to its nutrition ratio.\n\nTo produce a flower, the Anthurium must have enough **Ichor**.\n\nEvery time the Anthurium eats a creature, its max Ichor grows by an amount.\n\nThe plant will grow a tree at the beginning of a level and will very slowly spread. The plant has two phases. It begins in phase 1 and once the Anthurium's max nutrition reaches a threshold, it will enter phase 2 permanently.\n1. **Gather Nutrition**\nThe plant will be aggressive towards creatures and attempt to spread trees to other parts of the map. The plant becomes more aggressive as time elapses. During this phase, the plant grows fruits which can feed creatures. The plant will attempt to consume creatures. Once the plant has gathered enough Ichor, it will move onto its next phase.\n\n2. **Consume matter**\nThe plant will cease producing fruit and its parts will begin to transform  nearby tiles into **Anthurium Tiles** which are highly dangerous; creatures that step onto these tiles will be consumed within seconds.\nAnthurium Tiles corrupt adjacent tiles over time, transforming them.\n\n### Creatures\nThere exist a wide variety of creatures. There is a helpful chart to identify them.\n\n| Behavior Class | Description                                                           |\n| -------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| PASSIVE        | Does not attack other creatures OR flees when nearby other creatures. |\n| REACTIVE       | Only retaliates if provoked.                                          |\n| PREDATORY      | Actively hunts other creatures to satiate itself.                     |\n| FERAL          | Violent towards other creatures.                                      |\n| ALOOF          | Does not care about other creatures.                                  |\n\n| Consumer Type | Description                                                 |\n| ------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- |\n| AMBIENT       | Ichor is replenished passively over time given a condition. |\n| PROXIMITY     | Ichor is replenished when nearby a specific entity.         |\n| CONSUMER      | Ichor is replenished by consuming entities                  |\n| ESOTERIC      | Ichor is replenished through unconventional means.          |\n| EXEMPT        | Does not have ichor.                                        |\n\nCreatures can behave in vastly different ways and/or have mechanics around other existing mechanics. In this way, creatures are the actors and the stage for emergent chaos.\n\nSome creatures will create offspring given a condition.\n\nSome creatures are helpful, and some are harmful. It all depends on what their role is in the ecosystem.\n\n### Aura\nThe main currency of the game controlling how the game progresses and functions. Aura is gained by performing actions that affect other entities. Any action done by an actor that affects (or alters the state of) a victim gives points to the actor.\n\nAura can be gained by changing an entity's state. Repeated state changes have diminishing returns.\n\nA multiplier is built up by acting in quick succession or causing chain events.\n\n---\n\n# Completing levels\n\n### Defending yourself\nWhen playing as Pip, you are near the bottom of the food chain; there are creatures that are much more powerful than the player and will hunt you if they are hungry!\n\nPip is unique in that he is near defenseless on his own, only having an innate push ability. However, Pip starts with the unique ability to **pick up and throw** lightweight creatures and objects, which allows Pip to use external resources to solve situations. Pip can pick up a creature and squeeze it (by pressing the **Action** key) to make it cast its signature ability. Use this technique to kill other creatures, which may drop an Ability Shard imbued with its signature ability.\n\n### Encountering prefabs\nPrefab structures can be found in levels. They contain special creatures, items, or interactable entities. Most of the time, these structures can only be found or reached by using a special ability or under certain criteria.\n\n### Progressing to the next level\nThe player can only leave the level when the main boss of that level is defeated.\n\nTo summon the main boss, the player must break an Aura threshold.\n\nOnce the player reaches a sufficient amount of Aura, a boss will spawn positioned randomly on the map. The boss must be defeated to open a gate the player must escape through to advance to the next level. Once the boss has been spawned, the Anthurium will be forced into its phase 2 and will begin spreading very rapidly. \n\n\n### Boss\nThere is currently one boss; the **Mega Cow**. This boss is a PREDATORY CONSUMER and has the ability to charge through walls, destroying them.\n\n---\n\n# To be determined...\n- A long term goal/mystery for the player to solve\n- What sort of environments are to be explored\n\n# Components mandatory for entities\n\n| Component | Descriptions                                                                                                                                                                   |\n| --------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |\n| Health    | When this value reaches 0, the entity dies.                                                                                                                                    |\n| Ichor     | Replenished through eating and using items. Drained passively over time and by using abilities. When this value reaches 0, the entity starts taking ticks of damage over time. |\n| Aura      | Increased by interacting with entities. Interacting with entities in the same way consecutively increase Aura less.                                                            |\n| Opal      | Meta currency.                                                                                                                                                                 |\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-14810,
			"y":-6011,
			"width":639,
			"height":5840
		},
		{
			"id":"7343f5dd7292a8e5",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"- [ ] rework movement component into two: moveinputcomponent and physicscomponent\n- [ ] create claw animation for focks\n- [ ] make plant offensive\n- [ ] hook up the plant's \"emotions\"\n- [ ] doors to other lands???? like a labyrinth\n- [ ] rework growth node so that it can have an explicit location set",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-12550,
			"y":-8886,
			"width":520,
			"height":320
		},
		{
			"id":"c31338358c7fc04d",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"the anthurium core needs a brain and Lobes which do these functions:\n\n```\n--- GrowthLobe ---\ncheck if nutrition points > some threshold (500)\ncheck some other parameter\nif both conditions are met, then return high priority state switch\n```\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-12610,
			"y":-9346,
			"width":500,
			"height":420
		},
		{
			"id":"228c0a413e34c09e",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# State\n```\nreference to state machine\nan optional cooldown can be set, preventing this state from being switched to if the cooldown is still running\n\ncustom behavior can be set in this node\n\n+ reference to memory\n+ reference to additional components\n+ reference to other states (like a sequential behavior pattern)\n\nenter()\nupdate()\nphysics_update()\nexit()\n```",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-8510,
			"y":-9286,
			"width":480,
			"height":380
		},
		{
			"id":"1385e9ac9cad325a",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Lobe\n```\nreference to brain\nevaluate function, returns [float, BehaviorState]\ncommit function, commits any relevant data to Memory\n\n+ references to any relevant components\n+ hooks to any relevant signals\n  \ntranslates a condition created by external stimuli or internal state and returns a state (to be slotted into the state machine) and a priority (float value between 0.0 and 1.0)\n```",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-9720,
			"y":-9336,
			"width":510,
			"height":320
		},
		{
			"id":"646fc26f255d37c3",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Component\n```\na node which contains data and optionally some logic that alters the data.\na component should ideally serve one purpose.\n```",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-9210,
			"y":-8976,
			"width":440,
			"height":200
		},
		{
			"id":"16b1a7544554ca85",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"- DELETED `AnthuriumCoreComponent`\n- DELETED `AnthuriumPitcherComponent`\nThe pitcher might come back in the future but i don't really want it in the game right now. The Anthurium can be fed by dropping entities near its roots.\n- DELETED `PlayerComponent`\nThe components that define an entity as the \"player\" need to be isolated to allow the player to play as any entity they like.\n- DELETED `AnthuriumGrassComponent`\nMost of the things in this component (choosing a starting sprite, dying on contact with other plants, etc) were behaviors that are now new components.\n- CREATED `StageController`\n- CREATED `SpriteManipulator`",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-19710,
			"y":-9716,
			"width":500,
			"height":680
		},
		{
			"id":"385e170388bf06b3",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"dungeon cube guy\n1. align to grid\n2. charge energy\n3. move (until hit wall)\n4. align to grid\n5. charge energy\n6. move\n7. ...",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-19790,
			"y":-8996,
			"width":410,
			"height":300
		},
		{
			"id":"8de154e1cc1318bd",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Particle\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-17230,
			"y":-8096,
			"width":620,
			"height":460
		},
		{
			"id":"f457315981510ece",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# This is tough.\nSo i'm fixing the whole player -> entity thing.\n\nThe game will have the functionality which allows the player to control any entity through the mechanism of a virtual controller (`InputComponent` -> `AbilityManager`). Most living entities have `Brain` and `StateMachine` components. `Brain` components filter internal data and then switch states via the `StateMachine`. Currently, `BehaviorState` nodes tell the entity how to look and act. My issue is that when a player is controlling an entity, any sort of calls made to `InputComponent` by `BehaviorState` nodes should not be used. Instead, calls made to `InputComponent` by `PlayerManager` should be used. The `StateMachine` and `Brain` should still run so as to allow for visual effects or changes to the internals of the entity (for example, if an entity enters a frenzied state after being poisoned, then movespeed will change)\n\nThe player should be able to play as any entity they like.\nThere exists a virtual controller `InputComponent` that every entity hooks into to either move or cast abilities.\nHowever, if the player is controlling the entity, calls made to `InputComponent` within `BehaviorState` nodes should not be made. This can be controlled by using `player_controlled` which is inside `InputComponent`.\n\n```gdscript\n# BehaviorState\n\nif not input.player_controlled:\n\t# do stuff\n```\n\nSo then there's an immediate problem. How do i control visual effects? Normally i would do this within a BehaviorState but it's becoming increasingly obvious that this is not the proper way of doing things. I think that the visual side of things needs to be completely decoupled from states (and abilities), and should instead be entirely data-driven. But then how on earth do i do that? I suppose it would all be signal based. But it seems like there are too many bases to cover as far as events -> visual feedback go. Maybe i'm wrong about this.\n\nIf an entity uses an ability that has a windup, then a signal should be emitted and some sorta VFX node should pick that up and change the animation, maybe emit some particles, idk. But then how do i control for continuous animations? Like a walking, running, idling animation. \n\n> I guess layers of animations could be possible? The bottom layer would be the one set by the current state. The top layer would be the one set by an ability? IDK! this probably is no good; i would like to keep animations from `SpriteAnimator` or `DirectionalSpriteAnimator` to be single-track and these systems should be as simple and robust as possible.\n\nI'm honestly having a hard time grasping the purpose each one of my components should fill.\n\nThings that would cause visual feedback:\n- any property inside a component changes (singular)\n- current behaviorstate changes (singular)\n- current behaviorstate is the current behaviorstate (continuous)\n- an ability is\n\t- used (singular)\n\t- held (continuous)\n\t- finished (singular)\n\nBrain\n- determines a state to switch to\n- calculates priorities based on its child Lobes\n- whichever Lobe has the highest priority gets its state switched to\n\nLobe\n- stores a behaviorstate reference\n- uses internal data to calculate and return a priority value when prompted (0.0 - 1.0)\n\nStateMachine\n- allows for switching of states\n- calls the current state's process and physics process functions\n\nBehaviorState\n- calls input methods\n- changes internal state (components) based on external stimuli\n\nVFX (new?)\n- intercepts signals from multiple components to call visual effect functions\n- interfaces with a sprite animator / directional sprite animator",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-19090,
			"y":-9716,
			"width":560,
			"height":2000
		},
		{
			"id":"9444bbff43a13e2e",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"`AbilityShard`\n- Has `AbilityManager` with ability `ShardConsume` \n- `ShardConsume` takes an ability from the entity's linked `AbilityContainer` component and transfers them to the `subject`'s `AbilityManager`. \n\n`AbilityDropElement`\n- when interacted, destroys element in hand but spawns an `AbilityManager` with that `Ability`.\n- toggles the menu.",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-16330,
			"y":-8696,
			"width":380,
			"height":360
		},
		{
			"id":"ec2f04e887e34814",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"What needs to happen when an `Ability` is added to a creature?\n\n- Create the `Ability` node as a child of the `AbilityManager`\n- Register it with the `AbilityManager`\n- The `Ability` needs to link to nodes that are already present on the creature.\n\t- Singular nodes should not be created\n\t- Nodes which are commonly in multiple should be created\n\t- (if the ability calls for a hurtbox then the hurtbox should be created and added to the entity in code, and stored in an array to queue free later)\n\n",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-15910,
			"y":-8816,
			"width":480,
			"height":420
		},
		{
			"id":"149305f2c96fcd1a",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"1. activate AbilityHUDElement\n\tif hand state is not holding:\n\t1. store a reference of the element\n\t2. reparent sprite2d to hand\n\t\n\tif hand state is holding\n\t1. compare stored element data with new one\n\t2. if slot == slot, just reparent sprite2d back to the original element\n\t3. if slot != slot, swap ",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-16330,
			"y":-8916,
			"width":380,
			"height":200
		},
		{
			"id":"2f0b0c0b5d00cc34",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# The Anthurium, technically\n\nThe Anthurium is actually a collection of entities sharing one single brain, `AnthuriumBrain`. This is an autoload singleton script that keeps track of the current state of the Anthurium.\n\nThe Anthurium spreads slowly by placing `root`s down, which connect up with each other and provide `ends` for the Anthurium to continue its spread. If the Anthurium is pursuing a long-term goal, it is more likely to choose one of its `ends` that is closest to its goal.\n\n```gdscript\nextends Node\nclass_name AnthuriumBrain\n\nvar ends: Array[Entity] # <- the outermost roots will store themselves here\n```\n\nRoots are directional, where inbound connections point back to their origin point\n\n```gdscript\nextends Component\nclass_name AnthurRootComponent\n\nvar inbound: Array[Entity]\nvar outbound: Array[Entity]\n```",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-16990,
			"y":-7126,
			"width":760,
			"height":580
		},
		{
			"id":"c6e68f38ad0000bc",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Mid-round\nThe Anthurium is spreading.\nCreatures react to the anthurium in their own ways (fleeing, utilizing, killing).\nThe player explores room by room, interacting with the ecosystem and managing their ichor.\nThe state of the world builds toward a particular boss event. The player, if skilled, can read these signals and steer toward a preferred one.\nA round can last as long as the player allows it to, as long as a boss trigger doesn't occur.\n\n### Aura\nAura is a reflection of the vitality of the arena. Aura rises when the ecosystem is thriving (creatures/anthurium alive, ichor plentiful, terrain intact).\nAura falls when things are dying or being destroyed recklessly.\nThe player can drain Aura for short-term gain (kill things for special items/shards) or cultivate it for a stronger result screen score and potentially better boss event options. \n*(the boss should have an effect on aura somehow based on its behavior or nature)*\n\nAura rises when\n- Creatures are alive and active (multiplied by how many different creature species are active on the map)\n- The anthurium spreads\n- Terrain is intact\n- Ichor is abundant\n\nAura falls when\n- Creatures die\n- The anthurium is suppressed or killed back\n- Terrain is destroyed\n- Ichor goes scarce",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-18030,
			"y":-7192,
			"width":560,
			"height":866
		},
		{
			"id":"b25d09ad5578f54b",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# Boss event\nThere has been a natural event triggered by creature(s), the Anthurium, special terrain, or a timer, triggering a boss event.\n\nThe boss event will have a special objective that the player must complete in order to complete the round.",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-17560,
			"y":-6237,
			"width":460,
			"height":360
		},
		{
			"id":"e4bb52f4fc5bfb2e",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"# A new round begins\n\nThe player is returned to the game board and watches a new map be scrambled up before them. The player entity is then spawned in and the new round begins.",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-18590,
			"y":-7176,
			"width":300,
			"height":220
		},
		{
			"id":"d7b6987f692572f7",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"todo:\n# make the ability shard use ability\n\nhow do i do this? if the shard uses the ability, it will transfer an ability to its own abilitymanager.\n\nso somehow i need to transfer ownership. maybe through the recentlyinteracted component?",
